\begin_layout Standard
Instead of assuming that conspicuous consumption is limited to the rich
 and that the poor emulate unconditionally emulate them, we argue that the
 role of reference group is key to the idea of conspicuous consumption.
 Here, a conspicuous item either helps distance oneself from the others
 or provides a satisfaction of having achieved at least as much as others
 in the group.
 Both of these can evidently be defined only with respect to a point of
 reference.
 The poor do not therefore unconditionally emulate the rich but instead
 compare themselves to a particular reference point.
 But how does this reference point come about? 
\bar under
And would someone in a poorer position benefit from a 
\bar default
lowered status consumption.
 Given that the consumers do follow a reference point, what are the conditions
 when emulation of the rich may really pay off? We attempt to provide normative
 answers these questions using a model of consumption where the consumer
 optimise expected relative wealth relative to a reference.
\end_layout

