\begin_layout Standard
Status consumption - i.e.
 disproportionate amount of spending on items that serve no other purpose
 than boosting one's perceived status - relies on a particular notion of
 status - which for us is one's expected future wealth observed from with
 a particular reference group.
 More specifically, we differentiate a private view of status - which is
 limited to a particular reference group from the wider notion of status
 - which is independent of how status may be perceived from within the reference
 group.
 This makes empirical sense as since what status means to an individual
 differs from what it may mean for the group of individuals viewed at a
 higher level.
 While a high-status individual in one localised context may not be of high-stat
us in another, it is certain that the notions of power and net-asset-worth
 would be shared across multiple contexts (societies, communities, nations
 etc.) while the respective reference groups themselves would have a certain
 value in terms of status.
 More formally, in groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{i}\}_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 consumers in each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

, each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}n_{i}$
\end_inset

consumers may have a private view of status, but the notion of we associate
 with each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

is associated most certainly with the net wealth the group has amassed.
 Therefore while status at personal level might be subject to subjective
 uncertainties that are characteristic of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 the status at higher levels is indicated primarily by the material significance
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

